nventional "philosophy of history". It deals with the chaotic as well as the cosmic part of the human historical experience. It stages this drama through the tales that religious, mythical, literary, philosophical, folkloristic, and historiographical sources tell and which are retold and interpreted here. From early on humans wished to know where, why, and wherefore all started and took place. Couldn’t the dialectics between chaos and order be meaningful? Couldn’t they assume a productive role as to the world’s precarious event? Power, strife, guilt, divine grace and revelation, literary symbolization, as well as storytelling are discussed in this book. Philosophy, political theory, theology, religious studies, and literary studies will greatly benefit from its width and density.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aGeschichte. 4aKosmogonie. 4aUrsprünge. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aHistory.  acosmogony.  aorigins.  apolitics.1 aCarrasco, Davíd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanaoka, Eiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeyking, John von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoll, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanaino, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchabert, Tilo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchabert, Tilo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWensveen, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 avon Heyking, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dD